properties.docComment: reveals the top of the stack.
A read-only version of a game model.

An immutable description of a playing card. This abstraction is designed to
be independent of game logic, so it does not provide any service that relies
on the knowledge of the rules of any particular game.

This class implements the Flyweight design pattern: there can only ever be
one instance of a card that represents a specific real-world playing card
(such as Ace of Spades). In the absence of serialization and reflection,
this ensures that the behavior of the == operator is identical to that of
the equals method when two card arguments are provided.
Models a deck of 52 cards.

Component that shows the state of the discard pile and allows dragging
cards from it.
Represents the rank of a playing card.

Represents the four piles that must be completed to win the game, with the 
Ace at the bottom, face up, and all cards of the same suit on top, in 
sequence.

Places where a visible card can be located, except for the foundation piles
and the tableau.

Application class for Solitaire. The responsibility of this class is limited
to assembling the major UI components and launching the application. All
gesture handling logic is handled by its composed elements, which act
as observers of the game model.

A utility class to serialize and deserialize cards.

In serialized form, a card is represented as an integer between 0 and 51. A
stack of cards is represented as a semicolon-separated sequence of integers,
going in sequence from bottom to top.
Represents a general-purpose stack of cards.
Represents the suit of a playing card.
The different piles of the tableau.
Plays N games and computes the number of wins.
Represents anywhere a card can be placed in Solitaire.
Represents one possible action in the game.

Component that shows the deck and allows clicking it to draw cards. Listens
to game model state changes and updates itself to disappear if it is empty.
The different foundation piles.
Component that shows a stack of cards in the tableau.

A move that represents the intention to move pCard to pDestination, 
possibly including all cards stacked on top of pCard if pCard is in a
working stack.

Keeps track of the current state of the game and provides a facade to it. 

The game state can logically be separated into four distinct conceptual
elements: the deck, the discard pile, the foundations where completed
suits are accumulated, and the tableau, which consists of seven piles
where cards fan down in sequences of alternating suit colors.
Stores a string representing the card dragged.
Implementation of the Composite object in the composite design pattern.

Observer interface to be implemented by classes whose objects are interested
in being notified of a change in the state of the game model.
Never does anything.

Plays N games and, for each game, undo
all moves and redo them.

A class to store and manage images of the 52 cards and the back of a card.

To function properly, all 53 images must be accessible from a folder at
the root of the path from which the class file for CardImages is loaded.
If a file is missing or corrupted, launching the application will fail
with "Exception in Application start method" indirectly caused by
an ExceptionInInitializerError because this class will fail to 
initialize.

Represents seven piles of cards that fan downwards, where cards must be
stacked in alternating suit colors, and where cards can be moved from
pile to pile.

Component that shows a stack of cards in which a completed suit is
accumulated.

Game-playing behavior. Implementations of this interface
are responsible for ensuring that the sequence of Move 
instances returned does not put the game in and endless
cycle.
